\doTocEntry\toclof{}{\csname a:TocLink\endcsname{14}{x14-166003}{}{\numberline {6.1}{\ignorespaces A convex combination of the points $\x $ and $\y $ is given by $\z = \lambda \x + (1-\lambda )\y $ with any $\lambda \in [0,1]$. Here we demonstrate this using $\lambda = 2/3$. \relax }}}{302}\relax 
\doTocEntry\toclof{}{\csname a:TocLink\endcsname{14}{x14-166014}{}{\numberline {6.2}{\ignorespaces The green intersection of the convex sets that are the ball and the polytope is also convex. This can be seen by considering any points $x,y \in \text {Ball} \cap \text {Polytope}$. Since Ball is convex, the line segment between $x$ and $y$ is completely contained in Ball. And similarly, the line segment is completely contained in Polytope. Hence, the line segment is also contained in the intersection. This is how we can reason that the intersection is also convex.\relax }}}{311}\relax 
